The methodology used here was bootstrapping. I pulled SPTSX Index from Bloomberg and retrieved monthly returns since the year 2000 (which captures 2 market cycles). Here we are estimating 1 month future price, so we need a sample of monthly returns going back many years. I then used the probability distribution of 1 month returns to estimate the future distribution of the SPTSX Index. Momentum is one of the few factors that persist in the market and so I adjusted my estimates upward. Though there is a wide-spread belief there will be a recession in the next 12 months, I doubt it occurs in the next 1 month, so I revised upward.

If there is an escalation in the trade war or the Fed surprises the market with no cut or a hawkish cut at their September meeting then the index is likely to decrease. Previous events in the last year have seen the index fall up to 15%. The Fed hasn't pushed back against the market yet, but underlying economic data has been strong. I estimate a 25% chance of Fed pushing back and leading to a 10% fall in the index. Low odds of escalation in trade war as Trump is worried about effect on consumers over holidays.

Support seems to be 16,000 - has been tested over the past three months and has held. No indication of movement to the upside So I reallocated probabilities to reflect the heightened chance that it could fall below 16,000, feeling that the recent recoveries from touching 16,000 seemed week and without conviction. There's a decided downtrend to the index since late July, with lower highs at each recovery before reversal - as if institutions were selling into strength each time there's a rally....

Been in a trading range since April 2019 - having tested the high of 16,613 three times and fell back each time - the last fallback from July 21 2019 was noticeable. But always stayed above the 50 day MA. The prior high of 16561 was reached a year ago ---after which there was a 2500 point severe fall to just below 14,000 in mid-Dec 2018. So this market is spiky to the downside - and in 2015/2016 - was persistently spiky to the downside. Presently well above its 200 day MA. So - slight exposure to the upside. Slightly larger exposure to the downside. About where it is is about where it will be.

Given I don’t know much about Canadian stocks or their valuations, I would tend to believe the index will stay range-bound between 15-17,000 as it has for a few years now, likely due to heavy energy exposure in TSX/ Canada in general. Major upside risks would be increased energy prices, while major downside risks would be a Canadian housing related. Without much knowledge of what would cause either risk to happen, range-bound makes the most sense.
